insert into public.questions
  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(1638, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Rate Reconciliation$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'US', $x$A US company reports pretax book income of 1,000 but its effective tax rate is 18% versus a 21% federal statutory rate. Walk me through how you would build a rate reconciliation and name the kinds of items that drive the effective rate below statutory.$x$, $x$["Effective rate = total tax expense / pretax book income", "Start at statutory: 21% x 1,000 = 210 baseline", "Permanent differences move ETR; temporary do not", "Below-statutory drivers: tax-exempt income, FDII, R&D or other credits, foreign rate differential", "Above-statutory drivers: state taxes net of federal, nondeductible expenses, GILTI", "Valuation allowance changes also hit ETR", "Reconcile expressed in dollars or percentage points"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The effective rate is just total tax expense divided by pretax book income, so here total expense is 180 on 1,000. To bridge from the 21% statutory rate down to 18%, I start with the statutory tax of 210 and then layer on reconciling items in dollars or in percentage points. The key idea is that only permanent differences and discrete items move the effective rate; temporary differences do not, because they only shift tax between current and deferred. Items pushing the rate below statutory include tax-exempt income like municipal interest, the FDII deduction, R&D and other tax credits, and earnings in lower-rate foreign jurisdictions. Items pushing it above statutory include state taxes net of the federal benefit, nondeductible expenses like certain meals or fines, GILTI inclusions, and increases in a valuation allowance. So I would walk it as 210 less roughly 30 of credits and tax-exempt benefits, then plus a bit of state tax, landing at 180, and I would explicitly flag whichever driver is largest as the story behind the gap.$x$),
(1639, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Permanent Vs Temporary$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Explain the difference between a permanent and a temporary tax difference, give one clear example of each, and tell me which one creates a deferred tax balance and which one moves the effective tax rate.$x$, $x$["Temporary = timing difference that reverses, creates DTA or DTL", "Permanent = never reverses, no deferred balance", "Temporary example: accelerated tax depreciation vs book", "Permanent example: muni interest or nondeductible fines/goodwill impairment", "Permanent differences move the effective rate", "Temporary differences leave ETR at statutory over time", "Book vs tax basis framing"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A temporary difference is a timing difference between when something hits the books and when it hits the tax return, and crucially it reverses over time. Because it reverses, it creates a deferred tax balance, a DTL or a DTA, that unwinds in later periods. The classic example is depreciation: a company uses accelerated depreciation for tax and straight-line for book, so early on tax income is lower, you pay less cash tax now, and you book a deferred tax liability that reverses as the difference flips later. A permanent difference never reverses, so it never creates a deferred balance. Examples are tax-exempt municipal interest, which is income for book but never taxed, or a fine or a portion of goodwill impairment that is expensed for book but never deductible. The important distinction for analysis is that permanent differences move the effective tax rate away from statutory, because they change lifetime tax, while temporary differences leave the effective rate at statutory over time and only shift tax between current and deferred.$x$),
(1640, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Tax Rate Change$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$A company has a net deferred tax liability of 70 built up at a 35% rate from accelerated depreciation. Legislation cuts the statutory rate to 21%, effective immediately. Walk me through the remeasurement, the income-statement impact, and where it shows up even though the underlying difference relates to PP&E.$x$, $x$["DTL = temp diff x rate; implied temp diff = 70/0.35 = 200", "Remeasure at new rate: 200 x 21% = 42 DTL", "DTL falls by 28; credit to deferred tax expense", "Net income rises by 28 in enactment period", "Remeasurement hits continuing operations regardless of origin", "Recognize in period of enactment, not effective date", "Non-cash; no impact on current cash taxes this period"]$x$::jsonb, $x$First I back into the temporary difference. A 70 DTL at 35% implies an underlying book-versus-tax difference of 200. When the rate drops to 21%, I remeasure that same 200 difference at the new rate, so the DTL becomes 42. The liability falls by 28, and the offset is a credit to deferred tax expense, which means net income goes up by 28 in the period the law is enacted. A couple of nuances interviewers like. First, timing: you recognize the remeasurement in the period of enactment, not when the rate actually takes effect, so it can hit before the lower rate even applies. Second, location: even though this difference came from PP&E, the remeasurement of deferred taxes from a rate change is reported in continuing operations, not pushed back to wherever the item originated. And third, it is entirely non-cash this period; current cash taxes are unaffected. So the headline is a one-time, non-cash boost to net income and a lower effective rate that year, and going forward both the DTL unwind and the cash taxes reflect the lower 21% rate.$x$),
(1641, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Valuation Allowance$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$When does a company have to record a valuation allowance against a deferred tax asset? Walk me through the more-likely-than-not test, the sources of future taxable income that support a DTA, and how positive and negative evidence get weighed.$x$, $x$["VA is a contra-asset reducing a DTA to the realizable amount", "Test: more likely than not (>50%) the DTA will be realized", "Four sources of future taxable income support a DTA", "Sources: temp-difference reversals, future operating income, tax-planning strategies, carrybacks", "Objective evidence outweighs subjective forecasts", "Cumulative recent losses are strong negative evidence forcing a VA", "As negative evidence fades, allowance can be released"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A valuation allowance is a contra-asset that writes a deferred tax asset down to the portion you actually expect to use, and the test is the more-likely-than-not standard, meaning more than a fifty percent chance the DTA gets realized. The judgment is an evidence-weighing exercise. You look to four sources of future taxable income to support a DTA: reversals of existing taxable temporary differences, like a DTL unwinding against the DTA; projected future operating income; viable tax-planning strategies; and carryback availability. The key nuance is how the rules weight evidence: objective, verifiable evidence counts far more than subjective forecasts. So a recent history of cumulative pretax losses is strong, hard-to-overcome negative evidence that usually swamps a rosy projection, which is why a company with three years of cumulative losses typically must record a full allowance even if management is optimistic. As that negative evidence fades and positive evidence turns objective, the allowance can be released. My headline is that recording a VA turns on the quality of evidence, not just the point estimate of profit.$x$),
(1642, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Intraperiod Allocation$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$What is intraperiod tax allocation, and why does it matter that a company reports tax on continuing operations separately from tax on items like discontinued operations or amounts recorded in OCI? Give a practical example.$x$, $x$["Intraperiod = allocating total tax among IS, OCI, equity components", "Continuing-ops tax shown separately from discontinued/OCI", "Prevents distortion of continuing-ops effective rate", "Example: gain on discontinued op taxed within that line", "Example: tax on AFS securities or pension OCI booked in OCI", "Matches tax to the pretax item it relates to", "Analysts rely on a clean continuing-ops rate for forecasting"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Intraperiod tax allocation is the rule that a company splits its total tax for the period across the places the related pretax items live, so continuing operations, discontinued operations, other comprehensive income, and sometimes equity each carry their own tax. It matters because you want the tax shown against continuing operations to reflect only the recurring business, so the continuing-ops effective rate is clean and comparable for forecasting. If you dumped all the tax into continuing operations, a big one-time gain elsewhere could badly distort that rate. A practical example: if a company sells a division and books a large gain in discontinued operations, the tax on that gain is reported inside the discontinued line, not in continuing-ops tax. Similarly, the tax effect of unrealized gains on available-for-sale securities, or actuarial pension remeasurements, is recorded in OCI alongside the pretax amount. So each bucket of pretax income carries its matching tax, which keeps the income-statement tax rate representative of the core business I am actually modeling forward.$x$),
(1643, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Uncertain Tax Positions$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Conceptually, how does GAAP treat an uncertain tax position, sometimes called FIN 48, when a company takes an aggressive deduction it is not sure will survive an audit? Walk me through the two-step recognition and measurement idea and where the reserve sits.$x$, $x$["Two-step: recognition then measurement", "Recognition: more likely than not to be sustained on technical merits", "Measurement: largest benefit >50% likely to be realized", "Unrecognized tax benefit (UTB) reserve = liability", "Assumes tax authority has full knowledge, no audit-lottery", "Release on settlement or statute lapse flows to tax expense", "Interest/penalties accrued, often in the tax line"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The framework for uncertain tax positions is a two-step process. Step one is recognition: you record a benefit from the aggressive position only if it is more likely than not, over fifty percent, to be sustained on its technical merits, assuming the tax authority examines it with full knowledge of the facts. There is no audit lottery, so you cannot assume you simply will not get caught. If it clears that hurdle, step two is measurement: you record the largest amount of benefit that is more than fifty percent likely to be realized on settlement, which is often less than the full benefit claimed on the return. The piece you claimed but cannot recognize sits as a liability, the unrecognized tax benefit reserve. If the position later settles favorably or the statute of limitations lapses, you release the reserve and it flows through tax expense as a benefit, lowering the effective rate that period. Companies also accrue interest and penalties, frequently within the tax line. So the headline is that the company books a cushion against deductions that may not hold up, and reversals can be a lumpy driver of the effective rate.$x$),
(1644, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Acquisition Step-Up DTL$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$In a stock acquisition with no tax basis step-up, the buyer writes PP&E and intangibles up by 100 to fair value for book purposes. Walk me through why this creates a deferred tax liability at close, how it sizes, what it does to goodwill, and how it reverses.$x$, $x$["Book basis stepped up but tax basis unchanged in a stock deal", "Book > tax basis on an asset creates a DTL", "DTL = step-up x tax rate = 100 x 25% = 25 at close", "DTL recorded in purchase accounting increases goodwill", "Reverses as book depreciation/amortization of step-up exceeds tax", "No extra cash tax shield on step-up (tax basis unchanged)", "Contrast with asset deal/338(h)(10) where tax basis steps up"]$x$::jsonb, $x$In a stock deal the buyer generally inherits the target's old tax basis, so when you write PP&E and intangibles up by 100 to fair value for book purposes, book basis is now above tax basis but tax basis is unchanged. That gap, book greater than tax on an asset, is a taxable temporary difference, which means a deferred tax liability. It sizes as the step-up times the tax rate, so 100 at 25% is a 25 DTL recorded at close. Importantly, this is set up inside purchase accounting, and because the net identifiable assets are now lower by that 25 of liability, goodwill goes up by 25. The DTL then reverses over time: book depreciation and amortization on the stepped-up value exceed the tax deduction, so book tax expense is higher than cash tax in those years and the liability unwinds. The economic punchline is that in a pure stock deal you get the higher book D and A but no incremental cash tax shield, because the tax basis never moved. That is exactly why buyers prize structures like an asset deal or a 338(h)(10) election, where the tax basis does step up and the extra depreciation is actually deductible.$x$),
(1645, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Cash Vs Book Taxes$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$A company emerging from losses has a large NOL carryforward and is now solidly profitable. Its book effective tax rate looks roughly normal, but its cash tax rate is far lower. Walk me through why the two diverge, how the NOL DTA behaves, and what it means for a DCF.$x$, $x$["Book tax expense booked at ~statutory on pretax income", "NOL shelters taxable income so cash taxes are low", "Difference is deferred tax expense; DTA draws down", "Book ETR stays near statutory while NOL DTA exists", "Cash tax rate < book rate until NOL exhausted", "DCF uses cash taxes; model NOL as separate value or add-back", "Once NOL exhausted, cash rate converges to book rate"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The divergence comes from the NOL. On the books, tax expense is recorded at roughly the statutory rate on pretax income, so the book effective rate looks normal. But on the actual return, the NOL carryforward shelters taxable income, so the company writes a much smaller check, and the cash tax rate is far lower. The plug between the two is deferred tax expense, and the mechanism is that the NOL deferred tax asset draws down as it gets used. So each year, part of the book tax expense is non-cash, it is just the DTA shrinking, while the cash portion is small. The book rate stays near statutory the whole time the DTA exists, but cash taxes stay low until the NOL is exhausted, at which point the cash rate converges up to the book rate. For a DCF this matters a lot, because you discount cash taxes, not book taxes. So I would either run the NOL through the model so taxable income is sheltered in the early years, or value the company at a normalized cash rate and add the present value of the NOL tax savings as a separate line. Ignoring it understates value.$x$),
(1646, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Step-Up Deferred Tax$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$In a purchase price allocation you write the target's PP&E and intangibles up to fair value. Walk me through the deferred tax that this step-up creates, and explain how recognizing it changes the goodwill you book.$x$, $x$["Book carrying value steps up but tax basis unchanged in a stock deal", "Future book D&A exceeds tax D&A, so less tax shield than book implies", "Recognize a deferred tax liability equal to step-up times tax rate", "New DTL lowers net identifiable assets acquired", "Lower net identifiable assets grosses up the residual goodwill", "Asset deal steps up tax basis too, so no book-tax gap and no DTL"]$x$::jsonb, $x$When I do a purchase price allocation I push the acquired assets and liabilities to fair value, and one of the big steps that trips people up is the deferred tax that falls out of the step-up. Say I write the targets PP&E or an intangible up above its existing tax basis - for book purposes the asset is now carried higher, but the tax authorities still depreciate or amortize off the old, lower basis. So in future years book depreciation exceeds tax depreciation, the company gets less tax shield than the book number implies, and that future tax burden has to be recognized today as a deferred tax liability. I size it as the step-up amount times the tax rate. The important knock-on effect is on goodwill: because I have added a new liability to the balance sheet, the net identifiable assets are lower, so the residual - purchase price minus net identifiable assets - is larger. In other words, recognizing the DTL mechanically grosses up goodwill. A nuance is that in a non-taxable stock deal you get this book-tax gap and the DTL, whereas in an asset deal where tax basis also steps up, there is no gap and no DTL.$x$),
(1647, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Bargain Purchase Gain$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$You run the allocation on a distressed acquisition and the purchase price comes out below the fair value of the net identifiable assets. What do you do with that negative number, and what does accounting require before you book anything?$x$, $x$["Negative residual cannot sit as negative goodwill on the balance sheet", "First reassess identification of all assets and liabilities", "Re-check fair values, especially intangibles and contingent liabilities", "Presumption is a measurement error, not a true gift", "If still negative, recognize a gain in earnings on acquisition date", "Common in distressed or forced-sale situations"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A bargain purchase is the rare case where I pay less than the fair value of the net identifiable assets I acquire - so instead of a positive residual that becomes goodwill, the arithmetic gives a negative number. Accounting does not let me book negative goodwill on the balance sheet. The first thing I am required to do is go back and reassess everything - double-check that I have identified all the assets and liabilities, including contingent ones, and that my fair values, especially on hard-to-value intangibles and any pension or contingent liabilities, are right. The presumption is that a negative number usually signals a measurement error, not a true gift. If after that reassessment the figure is still negative, I recognize the difference immediately as a gain in the income statement on the acquisition date, attributable to the acquirer. These genuinely happen in distressed or forced sales, where a motivated seller offloads a business below fair value. So the headline is: reassess first, and only then run the leftover through earnings as a one-time bargain purchase gain, never as negative goodwill sitting on the balance sheet.$x$),
(1648, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Earnout Remeasurement$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A deal includes a cash earnout tied to the target hitting revenue milestones. How is contingent consideration recognized at close, and walk me through why a cash earnout can force a loss in earnings when the target outperforms.$x$, $x$["Record contingent consideration at fair value at acquisition, inside purchase price", "Earnout enters the goodwill calculation up front despite not being paid", "Classification drives subsequent accounting", "Cash-settled earnout is a liability, remeasured to fair value each period through earnings", "Higher expected payout raises the liability, booking a loss as target outperforms", "Fixed-share settlement is equity and is not remeasured", "Post-deal remeasurement hits earnings, not the original goodwill"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Contingent consideration is the earnout - extra payments to the seller that hinge on the target hitting future milestones like revenue or an approval. The key rule is that at the acquisition date I have to record it at fair value as part of the total purchase consideration, even though I have not paid it, so it goes into the goodwill calculation up front rather than being ignored until paid. The trickier part is classification, because it drives the subsequent accounting. If the earnout is a cash payment, it is a liability, and after the deal I remeasure that liability to fair value every period, with the changes flowing through the income statement as a gain or loss. So if the target outperforms and the expected payout rises, I book a loss in earnings even though the business is doing well - which feels counterintuitive. If instead the earnout is settled in a fixed number of my own shares, it is classified as equity and is not remeasured at all; it just sits there. One thing I am careful about: post-deal remeasurement adjusts earnings, it does not touch the original goodwill, because goodwill is frozen after the measurement period.$x$),
(1649, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Measurement Period Adjustments$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Six months after closing, the independent appraisal of an acquired intangible comes back different from the provisional number you booked. How do you account for it, and how would your answer change if instead a customer had walked away post-close?$x$, $x$["Measurement period up to one year to finalize provisional fair values", "Applies only to facts that existed at the acquisition date", "Adjust the asset and offset the change against goodwill", "US GAAP records it prospectively, with cumulative D&A catch-up in current earnings", "IFRS instead restates retrospectively to the acquisition date", "Post-acquisition events run through the income statement instead", "After the period closes the allocation is locked"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The measurement period is the window after closing - up to one year - during which I finalize my purchase price allocation as better information arrives about facts that already existed at the acquisition date. Deals close before every appraisal is done, so I book provisional amounts and refine them later. If within that year the valuation of an intangible comes back different from my placeholder, I adjust that asset with the offset against goodwill - more intangible value means less residual goodwill. Under US GAAP I record that in the current period, not by restating prior quarters: I book the asset and goodwill change and run the cumulative catch-up in depreciation through current earnings, as if I had the final number on day one. IFRS instead makes you restate retrospectively. The key distinction is cause: if the change reflects something that happened after the acquisition - an impairment post-close, or a customer that walks away later - that is not a measurement-period item, it hits the income statement as a current event. Once the year closes the allocation is locked and any later fix is a normal earnings item, not a goodwill tweak.$x$),
(1650, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Acquired IPR&D$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$You acquire a pharma company whose lead asset is still in clinical trials. How do you treat the in-process R&D in the allocation, and why is that different from how the acquirer treats its own internal R&D spend?$x$, $x$["Internal R&D generally expensed as incurred", "Acquired IPR&D recognized as an identifiable intangible at fair value, separate from goodwill", "Treated as indefinite-lived while in process, so not amortized", "Tested for impairment annually during the in-process phase", "On project completion it becomes finite-lived and amortization begins", "Written off if the project is abandoned"]$x$::jsonb, $x$In-process research and development is a project the target had underway that has not yet reached commercial viability - common in pharma or tech deals where the prize is a drug in trials or unfinished technology. The thing interviewers want is the contrast with how you would treat your own R&D. If I spend on R&D internally, I generally expense it as incurred. But when I acquire IPR&D in a business combination, I do the opposite: I recognize it as an identifiable intangible asset at fair value, separate from goodwill, because it is an identifiable resource I paid for. The subtle part is what happens next. Acquired IPR&D is treated as an indefinite-lived intangible while the project is still in process, so I do not amortize it; instead I test it for impairment each year. Once the project is completed - the drug is approved, the technology is finished - it becomes a finite-lived asset and I start amortizing it over its useful life. And if the project is abandoned, I write it off. So the headline is: internal R&D expensed, acquired IPR&D capitalized as an intangible, held without amortization until completion, then amortized.$x$),
(1651, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Full Vs Partial Goodwill$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$You acquire 80% of a target. Contrast measuring the non-controlling interest at fair value versus at its proportionate share of net assets. How does the choice change goodwill, NCI, and what each accounting regime allows?$x$, $x$["Full goodwill: NCI at fair value, goodwill grossed up to the whole entity", "Partial goodwill: NCI at proportionate share of identifiable net assets", "Full method gives higher goodwill and higher NCI", "Partial method books no goodwill on the minority stake", "US GAAP mandates full fair-value method; IFRS allows election per deal", "Partial goodwill must be grossed up before impairment testing"]$x$::jsonb, $x$This is the choice between full goodwill and partial goodwill, and it comes down to how I measure the non-controlling interest. Say I buy eighty percent of a target. Under the full-goodwill method I measure the NCI at its own fair value - essentially grossing the whole business up to a hundred percent - so goodwill reflects the entire entity, including the slice attributable to the minority holders. Under the partial-goodwill method, allowed under IFRS, I instead measure the NCI at its proportionate share of the targets identifiable net assets, so goodwill only captures the acquirers portion and no goodwill is booked on the minority stake. The practical effect: full goodwill produces a higher goodwill figure and a higher NCI on the balance sheet, with total equity grossed up; partial goodwill gives a smaller goodwill and a smaller NCI. US GAAP mandates the full-goodwill, fair-value approach, whereas IFRS lets you elect either method deal by deal. It also matters later for impairment - with partial goodwill you have to gross goodwill back up before running the impairment test so the comparison is apples to apples.$x$),
(1652, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Step Acquisition Remeasurement$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$You already hold a 30% equity-method stake and now buy another 30% to reach control. Walk me through what happens to the stake you already owned, and how you build the goodwill on the combined transaction.$x$, $x$["Crossing into control is treated as a significant economic event", "Remeasure the previously held interest to fair value at the date of control", "Difference between fair value and carrying amount goes through earnings", "Goodwill uses consideration paid plus fair value of prior stake plus NCI", "Less fair value of net identifiable assets", "Stop equity method and fully consolidate, showing an NCI", "Gain on remeasuring the old stake is the commonly missed step"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A step acquisition is where I already hold a stake and then buy more to get control - the classic case is going from, say, a thirty percent equity-method investment to a sixty percent controlling stake. The counterintuitive rule is what happens to the piece I already owned. Accounting treats crossing into control as a significant economic event, almost as if I sold my old stake and rebought the whole thing. So on the date I get control, I have to remeasure my previously held equity interest up - or down - to its fair value, and the difference between that fair value and its old carrying amount goes through the income statement as a gain or loss. Then goodwill is calculated on the whole thing: the fair value of what I just paid for the new shares, plus the fair value of my previously held interest, plus any NCI, less the fair value of the net identifiable assets. From that date forward I stop using the equity method and fully consolidate the target, showing a non-controlling interest for the portion I do not own. The gain on remeasuring the old stake is the part candidates usually forget.$x$),
(1653, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$VIE Primary Beneficiary$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A sponsor sets up a securitization vehicle and owns very little of its equity. Why might it still have to consolidate it? Walk me through the variable interest entity model and the primary-beneficiary test.$x$, $x$["Voting majority test can miss control through contracts and economics", "Entity is a VIE if equity holders lack control or equity is too thin", "For a VIE, drop the voting test and apply the primary-beneficiary test", "Primary beneficiary has power over the most significant activities", "And the obligation to absorb losses or right to significant benefits", "Power-plus-economics test, not an ownership test", "Relevant to post-Enron vehicles and today's private-credit structures"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The variable interest entity model exists because the normal consolidation test - who owns more than fifty percent of the voting shares - can miss situations where control runs through contracts and economics rather than votes. Think of a securitization vehicle or a JV with thin equity, where one party calls the shots and bears the risk without a voting majority. The rule says: if an entity is a VIE - meaning its equity holders lack real control, or the equity is too thin to absorb its own losses - then I drop the voting test. Instead, whoever is the primary beneficiary consolidates it. I am the primary beneficiary if I meet two conditions together: I have the power to direct the activities that most significantly affect the entitys economic performance, and the obligation to absorb losses or the right to receive benefits that could be significant to it. So it is a power-plus-economics test, not an ownership test. This is the framework that caught off-balance-sheet vehicles after Enron, and it is very relevant today with private-credit and securitization structures, where a sponsor can consolidate a vehicle it owns little equity in.$x$),
(1654, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Variable Consideration Constraint$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A medical-device distributor sells equipment with a volume rebate: if the hospital network buys more than 10,000 units in the year it gets a retroactive 8 percent rebate on everything. At contract start management thinks it is likely but not certain the threshold is hit. Under ASC 606 how do you set the transaction price, and what is the constraint?$x$, $x$["Rebate Is Variable Consideration, Estimate It Upfront", "Expected Value Or Most-Likely-Amount Method", "Volume Tier Suits Expected-Value Probability Weighting", "Constraint: Only Book Amount Highly Probable Not To Reverse", "Recognize Net Of Estimated Rebate, Refund Liability For The Rest", "Reassess Each Period As Volumes Become Known", "True-Up Revenue When Estimate Changes"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Under ASC 606 the rebate is variable consideration, so I cannot just book gross list price. Step three says I estimate the variable amount using whichever method better predicts the outcome - expected value, which probability-weights a range of scenarios, or most-likely-amount for a binary outcome. A volume-tier rebate across many units fits the expected-value approach, so I would weight the probability the network clears 10,000 units and lands the 8 percent. Then the constraint in step three bites: I only include variable consideration to the extent it is highly probable a significant revenue reversal will not occur later. So if it is merely likely the threshold is hit, I would haircut my estimate and record revenue net of the rebate I expect to grant, parking the difference as a refund liability rather than revenue. Crucially this is not a wait-and-see - I estimate from day one and then reassess every reporting period, truing up revenue up or down as actual volumes come in and the uncertainty resolves.$x$),
(1655, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Gross Versus Net Principal$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A food-delivery platform takes customer orders, the restaurant cooks the food, a third-party courier delivers it, and the platform keeps a 20 percent commission. A customer pays 50 dollars. Should the platform book 50 of revenue or 10? Walk me through the ASC 606 principal-versus-agent test and why it matters for valuation.$x$, $x$["Principal Recognizes Gross, Agent Recognizes Net Commission", "Test: Who Controls Good Or Service Before Transfer", "Indicators: Inventory Risk, Pricing Discretion, Primary Responsibility", "Platform Arranges Meal It Does Not Control - Likely Agent", "Net 10 Of Revenue, Not Gross 50", "Same Profit Dollars But Very Different Revenue And Margin Optics", "Drives EV/Sales Multiple And Take-Rate Disclosure"]$x$::jsonb, $x$This is the classic principal-versus-agent question, and it swings reported revenue by five times. The core test in ASC 606 is control: does the platform obtain control of the meal before it is transferred to the customer, or is it merely arranging for the restaurant to provide it? I would look at the indicators - who is primarily responsible for fulfillment, who bears inventory risk, and who has discretion over pricing. Here the restaurant cooks and stands behind the food, a third party delivers, and the platform never takes inventory risk on the meal, so it looks like an agent. As an agent it records revenue net - just its 20 percent, so 10 dollars, not the full 50. Notice the profit dollars are identical either way; what changes dramatically is the revenue line and the gross-margin optics. That matters enormously for valuation because marketplaces often get an EV/Sales multiple, so booking gross would inflate revenue and understate margin, and it drives how you read the company's take rate.$x$),
(1656, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Sales-Type Versus Operating Lease$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Forget the lessee side for a second - put me on the lessor. An equipment manufacturer leases a machine out for 7 years when the machine has an 8-year economic life. How do you decide between a sales-type lease and an operating lease under ASC 842, and how does the income-statement geography differ?$x$, $x$["Lessor Mirrors Lessee Finance-Versus-Operating Classification Tests", "Major Part Of Economic Life Or Substantially All Fair Value Transfers", "7 Of 8 Years Points To Sales-Type Lease", "Sales-Type: Derecognize Asset, Book Selling Profit Plus Interest Income", "Operating: Keep Asset, Depreciate It, Recognize Lease Income Straight-Line", "Net Investment In Lease Replaces The Asset", "Front-Loaded Versus Level Earnings Pattern"]$x$::jsonb, $x$On the lessor side ASC 842 runs essentially the same classification tests the lessee uses. If the lease transfers ownership, has a bargain purchase option, covers the major part of the asset's remaining economic life, the present value of payments is substantially all of fair value, or the asset is so specialized it has no alternative use, it is a sales-type lease. Seven years out of an eight-year life is the major part of economic life, so this is sales-type. That means the manufacturer derecognizes the machine, recognizes any selling profit upfront as if it sold the equipment - assuming collection is probable - and replaces the asset on the balance sheet with a net investment in the lease, then accretes interest income over the term. If instead it were an operating lease - say a short lease on a long-lived asset - the lessor keeps the machine on its books, keeps depreciating it, and just recognizes the lease payments as income straight-line. So sales-type front-loads earnings through day-one profit and interest, while operating gives a smooth, level revenue pattern.$x$),
(1657, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Capitalized Commissions And Modification$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A cybersecurity vendor pays its reps a 12 percent commission on the first-year value of a new 3-year subscription. Two questions: under ASC 606 do you expense or capitalize that commission, and then if the customer upgrades to a bigger plan mid-contract, how do you decide whether that is a separate contract or a modification of the existing one?$x$, $x$["Incremental Costs To Obtain A Contract Are Capitalized", "Commission Only Earned If Contract Signed - Incremental", "Amortize Over Benefit Period Including Expected Renewals", "Practical Expedient: Expense If Amortization Under One Year", "Modification Separate If Adds Distinct Goods At Standalone Price", "Otherwise Prospective Or Cumulative Catch-Up Reallocation", "Upgrade At Discount Usually Modification Not New Contract"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Two parts. First the commission: ASC 606 says incremental costs of obtaining a contract - costs you would not have incurred if the deal had not been signed - get capitalized as an asset, not expensed. A 12 percent commission paid only on a closed deal is textbook incremental, so I capitalize it and amortize over the period I benefit, which can stretch beyond the 3-year term to include anticipated renewals if the initial commission relates to them and renewal commissions are not commensurate. There is a practical expedient to just expense it if the amortization period is a year or less, but a multi-year sub does not qualify. Second the upgrade: I test whether it is a separate contract or a modification. It is a separate contract only if it adds distinct goods or services priced at their standalone selling price. A mid-term upgrade sold at a blended discount usually fails that, so it is a modification - and then I ask if the remaining goods are distinct. If they are, I account prospectively, reallocating the remaining consideration; if not, I do a cumulative catch-up adjustment.$x$),
(1658, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Significant Financing Component$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$An industrial-equipment maker takes a 5 million dollar payment upfront from a customer but does not deliver the custom machine until two years later. Separately, rates are higher-for-longer. How does ASC 606 treat the time value of money here, and which way does the adjustment cut when the customer pays in advance rather than in arrears?$x$, $x$["Significant Financing Component Adjusts Revenue For Time Value", "Customer Pays Upfront - Customer Is Financing The Seller", "Seller Effectively Borrowed, Accretes Interest Expense", "Revenue Recognized At Delivery Exceeds Cash Received", "Discount Rate Reflects Credit Of Party Receiving Financing - Here The Seller", "Higher Rates Widen The Adjustment", "Practical Expedient: Ignore If Under One Year"]$x$::jsonb, $x$When there is a meaningful gap between payment and delivery, ASC 606 makes me carve out the time value of money as a significant financing component, so revenue reflects the cash selling price, not the financing. Direction depends on who finances whom. Here the customer pays 5 million two years before getting the machine, so the customer is effectively lending to the manufacturer - the seller has an interest-free advance. So I treat it as a borrowing: I book a contract liability of 5 million and accrete interest expense over the two years, which increases the liability. At delivery the revenue recognized is the 5 million grossed up for that imputed interest, so revenue exceeds the cash collected, with the difference having run through interest expense. The discount rate reflects a standalone financing between the parties at inception, and since the seller is the one being financed here, it keys off the seller's borrowing rate and credit, not the customer's. With rates higher-for-longer that adjustment is larger than a few years ago. There is a practical expedient to ignore this if the gap is a year or less, but two years clears it.$x$),
(1659, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Sale-Leaseback Accounting$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A retailer sells its distribution center to an investor for 100 million and immediately leases it back for 15 years. Under ASC 842 walk me through how you decide whether this is a real sale, what gain it can book, and what changes if the leaseback is so long it is effectively a finance lease.$x$, $x$["First Test Whether A Sale Occurred Under ASC 606 Control", "Leaseback As Finance Lease Means No Sale - Failed Sale-Leaseback", "Failed Sale: Treat Proceeds As Financing, Asset Stays On Books", "Valid Sale: Derecognize Asset, Recognize ROU And Lease Liability", "Gain Recognized Only On Portion Of Rights Transferred To Buyer", "Off-Market Terms Adjusted To Fair Value", "Common Cash-Raising Tool, Watch For Hidden Leverage"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The first question under ASC 842 is whether a sale even happened, and you test that using the ASC 606 control criteria - did control of the building actually pass to the investor. The kicker is that if the leaseback is a finance lease, the seller has effectively kept control, so there is no sale at all. That is a failed sale-leaseback: you do not derecognize the asset, you keep the building on your balance sheet and treat the 100 million as a financing - basically a secured loan - with no gain. If instead it qualifies as a genuine sale with an operating leaseback, the retailer derecognizes the distribution center, records a right-of-use asset and lease liability for the leaseback, and here is the subtle part: it only recognizes the gain on the portion of the asset's rights that were transferred to the buyer, not the whole gain, because it retained a chunk of the asset's use through the lease. You also have to adjust for any off-market terms by marking the sale price and rent to fair value. In practice this is a popular cash-raising tool, and as a banker I would flag that the leaseback adds lease liabilities right back as quasi-debt.$x$),
(1660, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Lease Modification And Impairment$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A company downsizes - it renegotiates an office lease to give back two of five floors and cut the rent, and separately one of its retail ROU assets is now generating losses. Under ASC 842 how do you account for the partial lease termination, and how does ROU-asset impairment work and interact with the liability?$x$, $x$["Modification Not A Separate Contract - Remeasure Liability", "Remeasure At Revised Payments And Updated Discount Rate", "Partial Termination: Reduce ROU And Liability, Gain Or Loss To P&L", "ROU Impairment Tested Under ASC 360 Long-Lived Asset Rules", "Carrying Value Versus Undiscounted Cash Flows Recoverability Test", "Write ROU Down To Fair Value, Liability Unchanged", "Post-Impairment ROU Amortized Straight-Line Over Remaining Term"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Two separate mechanics. The give-back is a lease modification that is not a separate contract, so under ASC 842 I remeasure the lease liability using the revised payments and an updated discount rate as of the modification date. Because it is a partial termination - dropping two of five floors - I reduce the right-of-use asset and the liability, and any difference between the reduction in the asset and the reduction in the liability hits the P&L as a gain or loss. There is a choice of methods, either proportionate to the remaining ROU asset or to the decrease in liability. The impairment is a different regime: a loss-making ROU asset is a long-lived asset tested under ASC 360, not under the lease standard. So I run the recoverability test - compare the carrying amount of the asset group to its undiscounted future cash flows - and if it fails, I write the ROU asset down to fair value through the income statement. Critically, impairing the ROU asset does not touch the lease liability; I still owe the landlord. And after the write-down, the remaining ROU asset is amortized straight-line over the remaining term rather than via the old interest-style unwind.$x$),
(1661, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Performance Versus Market Conditions$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A company grants executives three flavors of equity: options that cliff-vest in 3 years, a tranche that vests only if cumulative revenue hits a target, and a tranche that vests only if the stock beats the S&P by 20 percent. Under ASC 718 how does the expense differ across these, and how does graded vesting and an ESPP fit in?$x$, $x$["Grant-Date Fair Value Fixed, Service Cost Spread Over Vesting", "Performance Condition Affects Whether You Recognize, Not Fair Value", "Reverse Expense If Performance Condition Not Met", "Market Condition Baked Into Grant-Date Fair Value Via Model", "Market Condition Expense Not Reversed Even If Unmet", "Graded Vesting Front-Loads If Treated As Separate Tranches", "Compensatory ESPP With Discount Or Lookback Generates Expense"]$x$::jsonb, $x$All three start from grant-date fair value, but the conditions are treated very differently under ASC 718. The plain options that cliff-vest are just a service condition: I take grant-date fair value and spread it over the 3-year service period, truing up only for actual forfeitures. The revenue-target tranche is a performance condition - it does not change the fair value, but it governs whether I recognize expense at all. If I think the target will be met I accrue; if it ultimately is not met, I reverse the cumulative expense, so comp can swing with the probability assessment. The market condition - beating the S&P by 20 percent - is the opposite: it gets baked into grant-date fair value through a Monte Carlo or similar model, and once set the expense is locked in. Even if the stock never beats the index, I do not reverse that expense; the risk is already priced in. On graded vesting, if the awards vest in annual chunks I can treat each tranche as its own award, which front-loads the expense. And a compensatory ESPP with a discount or a lookback feature is not free - that discount is measured and expensed like any other award.$x$),
(1662, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Net Periodic Pension Cost$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Walk me through the components of net periodic pension cost for a US-GAAP defined-benefit plan. Which pieces hit operating income, and how are actuarial gains and losses handled?$x$, $x$["Service Cost In Operating Expense", "Interest Cost Unwinds PBO Discount", "Expected Return Nets Against Interest", "ASU 2017-07 Non-Service Below Operating Income", "Actuarial Gains And Losses To OCI", "Corridor Amortization Into Earnings", "Funded Status On Balance Sheet Immediately"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Sure. Under US GAAP the net periodic pension cost that hits the income statement has a few pieces. Service cost is the present value of benefits employees earned this year, and it sits up in operating expense. Interest cost is the unwinding of the discount on the projected benefit obligation, and you net against it the expected return on plan assets - both of those, plus amortization items, now go below operating income in other income under ASU 2017-07, so only service cost is operating. Then actuarial gains and losses - from changes in the discount rate or experience differing from assumptions - are recognized in OCI, not net income, when they arise. They sit in accumulated OCI and get amortized into pension expense only when they fall outside a corridor, typically ten percent of the greater of the PBO or the market-related value of plan assets, spread over remaining service life. So the key idea is the funded status hits the balance sheet immediately, but the volatility from re-measuring it is parked in OCI and bled into earnings slowly.$x$),
(1663, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Settlement And Curtailment$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A company freezes its pension plan and later buys annuities to discharge part of the obligation. Explain the difference between a curtailment and a settlement and how each affects the income statement.$x$, $x$["Curtailment Reduces Future Service Accruals", "Settlement Irrevocably Discharges Obligation", "Curtailment Accelerates Prior Service Cost", "Settlement Recycles Deferred OCI Gains Losses", "Lump-Sum Drives Sudden Non-Cash Charge", "Treat As Non-Recurring When Normalizing"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Right, so a settlement and a curtailment are different events. A curtailment happens when you significantly reduce expected future service - say you close a plant or freeze the plan - so future benefit accruals stop. You immediately recognize any change in the PBO from that event, and you accelerate recognition of prior service cost tied to the lost years. A settlement is when you irrevocably discharge the obligation, for example buying annuities or paying lump sums, so you are off the hook. When you settle, you accelerate a pro-rata chunk of the unrecognized actuarial gains and losses sitting in accumulated OCI into the income statement right away, rather than amortizing them slowly. So the cash and the gain or loss can be lumpy. For a banker the point is that a big lump-sum settlement can drive a sudden non-cash charge as those deferred OCI losses get recycled into earnings, and you would treat that as non-recurring when you normalize.$x$),
(1664, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Debt Securities Classification$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$For debt securities, contrast trading, available-for-sale, and held-to-maturity classification. Where do the unrealized gains and losses go in each case?$x$, $x$["Trading At FV Through Net Income", "AFS At FV Through OCI", "HTM At Amortized Cost No Mark", "AFS Gains Recycled On Sale", "HTM Needs Intent And Ability", "Rising Rates Hit AFS OCI And Equity"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Sure. For debt securities, classification drives where the mark goes. Trading securities are carried at fair value with all unrealized gains and losses running straight through net income. Available-for-sale, or AFS, are also carried at fair value, but the unrealized gains and losses bypass the income statement and accumulate in OCI until you sell, at which point they get recycled into earnings. Held-to-maturity, or HTM, is different - you carry it at amortized cost, so there is no fair-value mark on the balance sheet at all, only interest income and any credit losses. The intent and ability to hold matters: HTM requires positive intent and ability to hold to maturity. So the same bond could show very different earnings volatility depending on the bucket. For a bank in a higher-for-longer rate world, that AFS-versus-HTM choice is huge, because rising rates push AFS marks into OCI and dent tangible equity even though earnings look fine.$x$),
(1665, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Equity Securities FVTNI$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Post ASU 2016-01, how do you account for an equity investment that is neither consolidated nor equity-method? What does that mean for reported earnings and how you normalize them?$x$, $x$["Fair Value Through Net Income Default", "Pre-2016-01 AFS Mark In OCI", "Unrealized Swings Hit Income Statement", "Cost-Minus-Impairment Practicality Election", "Adds Quarterly Earnings Volatility", "Strip Unrealized Gains When Normalizing"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Yes. Before ASU 2016-01 you could park most equity investments in available-for-sale and let the mark sit in OCI. That changed - for most equity securities that are not consolidated and not equity-method, you now carry them at fair value with the changes flowing through net income each period, what people call FVTNI. So an unrealized gain or loss on a stake in a public company hits the income statement directly, which can add real earnings volatility quarter to quarter. There is a practicality election for equity securities without readily determinable fair values - you can measure them at cost minus impairment plus or minus observable price changes. The big takeaway for valuation is that reported net income now embeds these mark-to-market swings on equity stakes, so when I normalize earnings I strip out those unrealized investment gains and losses, because they are non-operating and non-cash, and they distort a clean read on the core business.$x$),
(1666, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$CECL Expected Credit Losses$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$Explain the CECL model and how it differs from the old incurred-loss approach. Why does it matter for a lender's earnings, and how does it apply differently to AFS debt?$x$, $x$["Lifetime Expected Loss On Day One", "Replaces Probable Incurred-Loss Model", "Forward-Looking Macro Forecasts Drive Reserve", "Provision Expense At Origination", "AFS Separate Model Capped At FV Shortfall", "Provisions Swing Before Actual Defaults"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Sure. CECL stands for current expected credit losses, and it replaced the old incurred-loss model for amortized-cost assets like loans and held-to-maturity debt. Under the old rules you waited until a loss was probable before reserving. CECL flips that - on day one you book a lifetime expected loss allowance for the asset, based on historical experience, current conditions, and reasonable forward-looking forecasts. So you recognize an allowance through a provision expense the moment you originate the loan, even if nothing has gone wrong yet. That front-loads loss recognition and makes reserves more sensitive to the macro outlook. AFS debt sits in a separate model - you only book a credit allowance once fair value is below amortized cost and there is actual credit impairment, and the allowance is capped at that fair-value shortfall, kept apart from the rate-driven piece in OCI. For a lender, especially with private credit at scale, CECL means provisions swing with the forecast, so a worsening outlook can hit earnings well before any actual default shows up.$x$),
(1667, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Fair-Value Hierarchy$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Walk me through the three levels of the fair-value hierarchy under ASC 820. Why should a banker doing diligence care how much of a balance sheet is Level 3?$x$, $x$["Hierarchy Ranks Inputs Not Assets", "Level 1 Quoted Prices Active Markets", "Level 2 Observable Inputs Similar Instruments", "Level 3 Unobservable Model Assumptions", "Lower Level More Judgment And Disclosure", "Heavy Level 3 Is Diligence Red Flag"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Right. The fair-value hierarchy under ASC 820 ranks the inputs you use to measure fair value, not the assets themselves, into three levels by how observable they are. Level one is quoted prices in active markets for identical assets - think a listed stock or a Treasury - the most reliable, no judgment. Level two uses observable inputs other than quoted prices, like quoted prices for similar instruments, or yields and spreads you can observe, so a lot of corporate bonds and many derivatives land here. Level three is unobservable inputs - your own assumptions and models - used when there is no market data, like a private equity stake, a complex structured product, or an illiquid loan. The lower you go, the more management judgment and the more disclosure required, including a roll-forward of level three. For a banker doing diligence, a balance sheet heavy in level three marks is a red flag, because those values rest on assumptions that are hard to verify and easy to flatter.$x$),
(1668, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Net Investment Hedge$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A US parent owns a euro-functional subsidiary and wants to hedge its net investment. How does a net investment hedge work, where do the gains and losses go, and when do they hit earnings?$x$, $x$["Hedges FX On Foreign-Sub Net Equity", "Hedge Via FX Debt Or Forward", "Effective Portion Gain Loss To OCI", "Offsets CTA In Same OCI Account", "Deferred Until Disposal Of Operation", "Both Recycled To Net Income On Exit"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Sure. A net investment hedge protects the parent against currency swings on its net investment in a foreign operation - basically the equity of a foreign subsidiary whose functional currency is not the parent. Say a US parent owns a euro-functional sub; if the euro weakens, the dollar value of that net investment falls, and that shows up as a negative cumulative translation adjustment in OCI. To hedge it you might take on euro-denominated debt or a forward, and designate it as a net investment hedge. The effective portion of the gain or loss on that hedging instrument also goes to OCI, into the same cumulative translation account, so it offsets the translation swing on the investment rather than hitting earnings. It sits there until you dispose of the foreign operation, and then both the CTA and the accumulated hedge result get recycled into net income together. So it is an OCI-on-OCI offset that smooths reported equity, and the earnings impact is deferred until exit.$x$),
(1669, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Remeasurement Versus Translation$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$How do you determine a foreign entity's functional currency, and how does that choice drive remeasurement versus translation? What happens to the CTA on disposal?$x$, $x$["Functional Currency Of Primary Economic Environment", "Local Functional Means Current-Rate Translation", "Translation Plug To CTA In OCI", "Parent Functional Means Temporal Remeasurement", "Remeasurement Gain Loss Hits Net Income", "Hyperinflationary Forces Remeasurement", "CTA Recycled To Earnings On Disposal"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Right. The first question is the functional currency of the foreign entity - the currency of the primary economic environment where it operates, based on where it generates and spends cash, its pricing, its financing. That determination drives the method. If the functional currency is the local currency, you use translation, the current-rate method: assets and liabilities at the period-end spot rate, income statement at the average rate, and the plug from rate changes goes to the cumulative translation adjustment in OCI - it does not touch earnings. If instead the functional currency is the parent's, say because the entity is just an extension of the parent or operates in a hyperinflationary economy, you use remeasurement, the temporal method: monetary items at the current rate, non-monetary items at historical rates, and the gain or loss runs through net income. The big distinction is translation goes to OCI and is non-cash, while remeasurement hits the P&L. And on disposal of the foreign operation, that parked CTA balance gets recycled out of OCI into the income statement as part of the gain or loss on sale.$x$),
(1670, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Treasury Stock Method$x$, 'core', 3, 'intern', 'Global', $x$Walk me through the treasury stock method for diluted EPS. Say a company has 50 million basic shares, net income of 200 million, and 2 million employee options with a 20 dollar strike when the average share price is 50 dollars. What is diluted EPS, and when do options actually dilute?$x$, $x$["Assume options exercised, proceeds used to buy back shares at average market price", "Proceeds equal strike times options, plus any unamortized comp cost", "Net new shares equal options minus shares repurchased", "Here 2M options, 40M proceeds buys back 800K, so 1.2M net new shares", "Basic EPS 4.00, diluted shares 51.2M, diluted EPS about 3.91", "Only dilutive when in the money, average price above strike", "Out-of-the-money or antidilutive options are excluded"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The treasury stock method assumes the in-the-money options get exercised, and the company uses the cash proceeds to buy back its own shares at the average market price during the period. So I start with the proceeds: 2 million options times the 20 dollar strike is 40 million dollars, and I would add any unamortized stock comp expense to that. At a 50 dollar average price, 40 million buys back 800 thousand shares. The net new shares are the 2 million issued minus the 800 thousand repurchased, so 1.2 million incremental shares. Basic EPS is 200 over 50 million, which is 4.00. Diluted shares are 51.2 million, so diluted EPS is roughly 3.91. The key intuition is that options only dilute when they are in the money, meaning the average price sits above the strike, because then the proceeds cannot buy back all the shares issued. If options are out of the money, or if including them would raise EPS, they are antidilutive and you leave them out entirely.$x$),
(1671, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$If-Converted Method$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$How does the if-converted method differ from the treasury stock method, and when do you use it? Run it for a 500 million convertible bond with a 3 percent coupon that converts into 10 million shares, given net income of 200 million, 50 million basic shares, and a 25 percent tax rate.$x$, $x$["If-converted used for convertible bonds and convertible preferred", "Add back after-tax interest to the numerator", "Add conversion shares to the denominator", "Interest 15M, after-tax add-back 11.25M", "Diluted EPS roughly 211.25M over 60M equals about 3.52 vs basic 4.00", "Include only if dilutive, compare incremental EPS to basic", "Contrast with treasury method which adjusts only the denominator"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The treasury stock method adjusts only the share count and is used for options and warrants. The if-converted method is for convertible securities like convertible bonds or convertible preferred, and it touches both the numerator and the denominator. The idea is you pretend conversion happened at the start of the period, so the company never paid the interest and the new shares were outstanding the whole time. For this bond, annual interest is 3 percent of 500 million, which is 15 million. I add that back net of the 25 percent tax, so 11.25 million goes back to the numerator because the interest deduction disappears. Then I add the 10 million conversion shares to the 50 million basic, giving 60 million. Diluted EPS is 211.25 million over 60 million, about 3.52, versus basic of 4.00, so it is dilutive and I include it. I only include a convertible if it lowers EPS. The incremental EPS from conversion here is 11.25 over 10 million, about 1.13, and since that is below basic EPS of 4.00 it dilutes.$x$),
(1672, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Cash Flow Classification$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Tell me where each of these lands on the cash flow statement and why: capitalized interest on a construction project, cash paid to acquire a business net of cash acquired, principal versus interest on a finance lease, and dividends paid. Any that trip people up?$x$, $x$["Capitalized interest is part of capex, so investing outflow not operating", "Cash interest paid still disclosed even when capitalized into the asset", "Acquisition of a business is investing, shown net of cash acquired", "Finance lease principal is financing, interest is operating or financing per policy", "Operating lease payments sit in operating activities", "Dividends paid are financing; under US GAAP interest paid is operating", "Classification choices affect operating cash flow comparability"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Capitalized interest is the sneaky one. Even though it is interest, once it is capitalized into a construction project it becomes part of the asset, so the cash shows up in investing as part of capex, not in operating. The total interest paid still gets disclosed, but the capitalized slice is investing. Cash paid for an acquisition goes in investing, shown net of any cash that came with the target, so a cash-rich target reduces the reported outflow. On a finance lease, the repayment splits: the principal portion is a financing outflow and the interest portion under US GAAP is typically operating, though policy can vary. Contrast that with an operating lease, where the whole payment runs through operating. Dividends paid are financing. The thing to watch is that under US GAAP interest paid and received are operating while dividends paid are financing, whereas IFRS gives you more choice. These classification calls matter because shifting items in or out of operating activities changes the operating cash flow people anchor on.$x$),
(1673, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Convertible Debt ASU 2020-06$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'US', $x$After ASU 2020-06, how is plain-vanilla convertible debt accounted for, and how did that change reported interest expense, EPS, and the diluted share count versus the old split-accounting model?$x$, $x$["Old rules split convertible into liability and equity components", "Equity component created a debt discount amortized as extra interest", "ASU 2020-06 removed cash conversion and beneficial conversion models", "Most converts now a single liability at amortized cost, no discount", "Result is lower non-cash interest expense and higher reported earnings", "Diluted EPS now requires if-converted, treasury stock method no longer allowed", "Assume share settlement for diluted EPS regardless of intent"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Before ASU 2020-06, a lot of convertibles were split into a liability piece and an equity piece, especially under the cash conversion model. Carving out the equity component left the debt recorded at a discount, and that discount got amortized back as extra non-cash interest expense, so reported interest was well above the cash coupon and earnings looked lower. The standard largely killed that. Now most plain-vanilla convertibles sit as a single liability at amortized cost with no separation, unless there is a substantive feature like a true derivative. The practical effects are that interest expense drops to roughly the coupon plus issuance cost amortization, so reported net income rises. On the EPS side, the rules also changed the denominator: you must use the if-converted method and can no longer use the treasury stock method for these, and you assume share settlement even if the company intends to settle the principal in cash. So diluted share counts generally went up while interest expense came down.$x$),
(1674, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Cloud And Internal-Use Software$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$A company builds an internal ERP system and separately pays to implement a hosted cloud SaaS platform it does not own. How do you decide what to capitalize in each case, where the amortization shows up on the income statement, and how the cash flows are classified?$x$, $x$["Internal-use software follows ASC 350-40 three-stage model", "Preliminary and post-implementation stages expensed, development stage capitalized", "Owned software amortization and capex run through investing for cash", "Cloud computing arrangement implementation costs follow ASU 2018-15", "CCA implementation costs capitalized like internal-use software over the term", "CCA amortization presented in same IS line as the hosting fees, operating expense", "CCA implementation cash flows classified as operating, matching service fees"]$x$::jsonb, $x$For the internally built ERP, I follow the three-stage model in ASC 350-40. Preliminary project costs, the scoping and evaluation work, get expensed. Once it is probable the project will be completed and used, the application development stage costs, coding, configuration, testing, get capitalized. Then post-implementation costs like training and maintenance go back to expense. The capitalized asset is amortized straight-line over its useful life, that amortization is an operating expense, and the upfront spend is capex that hits investing on the cash flow statement. The hosted SaaS platform is different because the company does not own the software, so it is a service contract. Under ASU 2018-15 you can still capitalize the implementation costs, applying the same staging logic, but the amortization is presented in the same income statement line as the hosting fees rather than as depreciation, and importantly the cash outflows for those implementation costs are classified as operating, alongside the subscription fees, not investing. So similar capitalization, very different geography.$x$),
(1675, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Warrant Classification$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$What determines whether warrants are classified as a liability versus equity, and what are the income-statement and EPS consequences of each? This came up a lot with SPAC warrants.$x$, $x$["Equity classification requires indexed to own stock and equity settlement, ASC 815-40", "Liability if net cash settlement possible or settlement terms fail the tests", "Features like different payouts by holder class pushed SPAC warrants to liability", "Liability warrants remeasured to fair value each period through earnings", "Creates non-cash, non-operating volatility in net income", "Equity warrants recorded once in equity, not remeasured", "EPS uses treasury stock method when dilutive, watch antidilution"]$x$::jsonb, $x$It comes down to the settlement and indexation analysis in ASC 815-40. To sit in equity, a warrant has to be both indexed to the company own stock and capable of equity settlement that the issuer controls. If there is any path to net cash settlement outside the company control, or if the terms could pay different holders differently, it fails the indexed-to-own-stock test and becomes a liability. That second point is exactly what tripped up a wave of SPAC warrants, where features tied to who held them forced liability treatment. The accounting consequence is meaningful. Liability-classified warrants are remeasured to fair value every reporting period, with the change running through the income statement, so as the share price moves you get non-cash, non-operating swings in net income that have nothing to do with the business. Equity-classified warrants get recorded once in equity at issuance and are never remeasured, so earnings are clean. For diluted EPS, in-the-money warrants generally come in through the treasury stock method, though you exclude them when antidilutive.$x$),
(1676, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Asset Retirement Obligations$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$An energy company must dismantle a facility at the end of its life. Walk me through how an asset retirement obligation is recognized and how it flows through the three statements over time, including the cash flow geography.$x$, $x$["Recognize ARO liability at present value of expected retirement cost", "Capitalize an equal amount into the long-lived asset, the ARC", "ARC asset depreciated over the asset useful life, operating expense", "Accretion expense unwinds the discount each period, grows the liability", "Both depreciation and accretion are non-cash, added back in operating", "No cash moves until actual settlement at retirement", "Settlement outflow timing and section depend on facts, often operating or investing"]$x$::jsonb, $x$When the obligation to dismantle becomes determinable, you recognize a liability today at the present value of the expected future retirement cost, using a credit-adjusted risk-free rate. The offset is not an expense; you capitalize the same amount into the long-lived asset as an asset retirement cost, so the gross asset grows. From there, two things hit the income statement each period. First, that capitalized cost is depreciated over the asset useful life, which is an operating expense. Second, the liability gets accreted, meaning you unwind the discount so the present value grows toward the undiscounted amount, and that accretion is an expense that looks like interest. Both are non-cash, so on the cash flow statement they get added back within operating activities, and the liability and net asset sit on the balance sheet. No actual cash moves until you finally retire the facility and pay to dismantle it, often many years out. At settlement you relieve the liability and book a gain or loss versus the estimate, with the cash outflow classified based on the nature of the activity.$x$),
(1677, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Discontinued Operations$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A company decides to sell a business segment and classifies it as held for sale. What changes on the financial statements, how do you measure the held-for-sale assets, and when does it qualify as a discontinued operation rather than just a normal asset sale?$x$, $x$["Discontinued op requires a component disposal that is a strategic shift", "Results reported separately, net of tax, below continuing operations", "Prior periods recast so continuing ops are comparable", "Held-for-sale measured at lower of carrying amount or fair value less costs to sell", "Depreciation and amortization stop once classified held for sale", "Held-for-sale assets and liabilities presented separately on balance sheet", "Cash flows often disclosed; EV and multiples should use continuing ops"]$x$::jsonb, $x$First, the threshold matters. A disposal only counts as a discontinued operation if it is a component of the entity and the disposal represents a strategic shift with a major effect on operations, like exiting a whole line of business or geography. A routine sale of one asset does not qualify. If it does qualify, the segment results get pulled out of continuing operations and shown as a single net-of-tax line for discontinued operations, and prior periods are recast the same way so continuing operations are comparable. On measurement, once the segment is classified as held for sale you stop depreciating and amortizing its assets, and you carry the disposal group at the lower of its carrying amount or fair value less costs to sell, taking an impairment if needed. On the balance sheet the held-for-sale assets and liabilities are presented separately, usually as current. For analysis, this is why you build multiples and enterprise value off continuing operations, so you are valuing the business that will actually remain after the sale closes.$x$),
(1678, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Two-Class And Contingent Shares$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Explain the two-class method for EPS and how it differs from treating participating securities as options. Separately, how do contingently issuable shares, like an earnout payable in stock, enter the diluted share count?$x$, $x$["Two-class method allocates earnings to common and participating securities", "Participating securities share in dividends or undistributed earnings", "Allocate based on dividend and participation rights, then divide each class", "Differs from if-converted or treasury method which assume conversion", "Contingently issuable shares included if conditions are met at period end", "Test as if reporting date were the end of the contingency period", "Earnout shares excluded until the contingency, like a target, is satisfied"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The two-class method applies when a company has participating securities, instruments that share in earnings alongside common, like certain preferred or restricted stock that gets dividends. Instead of assuming conversion, you allocate the period earnings between common and each participating class based on their rights to dividends and to undistributed earnings, then you divide each bucket by its own share count to get EPS for the common. That is different from the if-converted or treasury stock approaches, which assume the security becomes common shares; here you respect that it participates while staying a separate class. On contingently issuable shares, think of a stock-settled earnout. The rule is you include those shares in diluted EPS only to the extent the contingency would be met if the reporting date were the end of the contingency period. So if the earnout target, say a revenue or earnings hurdle, is already satisfied as of period end, the shares are in; if it is not yet met, you exclude them even if management expects to hit it later. A pure time condition that will lapse is treated as met.$x$);
